removed.title: Meet Tygra
removed.description: The smartest Thundercat, Tygra. Tygra's mission is to make Lion-O a better leader. He might get around to it too, if he wasn't so busy cleaning up after the other Thundercats.

removed.title: Meet The Thunderkittens
removed.description: The Thunderkittens might be the youngest Thundercats, but Wilykit and Wilykat are a dynamic brother and sister duo! They'll help take down any foe, even if they don't really know what their own capsule weapons can do.

removed.title: Steven Universe Ultimate Catch-Up Trailer
removed.description: Take a look back on Steven's journey with this ultimate catch-up trailer!

removed.title: We Bare Bears The Movie: Behind the Scenes Artwork
removed.description: Check out some early artwork, pencil tests and animatics from We Bare Bears the Movie!

removed.title: It's a Trap
removed.description: Lex Luthor plays a deadly game of "know thine enemy," baiting Superman into a remote hideout in search of a kidnapped woman named Brie Gruyere. The super hero pounds Lex through the ceiling of another building housing the victim, where the "girl" turns out to be a Kryptonite gas spewing robot. As Superman and Lex ponder aloud the predictability of a foe's actions, it looks like Lex, armed with a Kryptonite club, is winning. But he may not know his enemy as well as he thinks.

removed.title: Good Cop, Bat Cop
removed.description: Deadshot's been enlisted to put a hit on Batman but with Superman's help they thwart his plan and take him into custody. Stuck in a barren interrogation room, Superman offers to play bad cop for a change but he's such a decent guy that Deadshot just laughs at him. Batman's attempt at playing good cop though seems to make an impression on the villainous creep, and definitely not a good one.

removed.title: Missing the Mark
removed.description: When Mark Hamill ("Famous Actor") hails a car for a lift to the Gotham City Conservatory, his driver is none other than The Joker ("Master Villain"), accompanied by Trickster ("2nd Rate Villain"). Mark is lashed to the back seat as the Joker prepares to ransom him to the studios, "who'll pay plenty to get you back!" When the police give chase, the Joker and his "witless wannabee's" argument gets heated, causing the Joker to crash the car into a thicket in the middle of the road, Swamp Thing. Whatever could make the two villains go at each other so?

removed.title: Selfie Help
removed.description: Space Cabbie is willing to write off Batman's $38,000 fare in exchange for a selfie with the super hero, to no avail. Inside Justice League headquarters, he spots Booster Gold in a Batman costume, who wants hawk his own Golden Fizz drink brand in the picture then proceeds to photobomb all of Cabbie's shots. When he stumbles into an isolated room where Wonder Woman battles a group of violent attackers, Cabbie has to decide: selfies of the fight, or help an outnumbered super hero!

removed.title: Justice 1, 2, 3, Go!
removed.description: Under heavy ground fire, Batman, Wonder Woman, Plastic Man, and Cyborg search for the HIVE headquarters from their aircraft. But HIVE has cloaked its entire operation. The team splits, with Wonder Woman in Justice II and the others in tanks. An excited Plastic Man accidentally deploys the submarine instead, falling into a treetop. Wonder Woman is shot out of the sky and Batman is outmaneuvered and immobilized. It'll take a miracle to get out of HIVE's crosshairs.

removed.title: Skyjacked
removed.description: Under cover of night, Justice One streaks away from the Tower with Poison Ivy and Harley Quinn at the controls! The Batwing interrupts their short lived victory. Struck by one of their missiles, the Batwing starts to plummet. Batman slings a grappling hook onto Justice One and tries to get aboard, only to be launched back into the air on the craft's many separate aircraft, including a submarine. Batman gets aboard to face off with Ivy and Harley, but a smashed guidance system sends the ship plummeting. Batman buckles in. What is he doing?

removed.title: Special Delivery
removed.description: In a bad part of town, Space Cabbie primps waiting for a fare. When Booster Gold and a purple alien bug in labor fight over who gets the cab, Granny Goodness and her minions from Apokolips attack, trying to get Booster Gold. Space Cabbie heads for the hospital as the roof is torn off and Granny Goodness drops in to help with the delivery, with evil intentions for the baby alien. Now Booster Gold has to decide whether to protect the newborn and its mom or try to hitch a ride back to Earth.

removed.title: The Goddess Must Be Crazy
removed.description: Wonder Woman and Supergirl are in a practice mid air combat over Themyscira stadium, and Supergirl loses the round but damages the statue of a horse. Wonder Woman tells her that because of a battle between Superman and Batman, she's taken steps to keep men out of Themyscira. As they continue to train, sorcerer Felix Faust emerges from the broken statue and takes over Supergirl's body. His goal: use her to vanquish Wonder Woman and steal some tempting magical Amazonian artifacts from Themyscira.

removed.title: Driver's Ed
removed.description: Space Cabbie is giving a skittish Stargirl a driving lesson through an asteroid belt. "You just need to stop worrying about the things around you and focus on something ahead of you."  Her sense of justice kicks in when she spots Zilius Zox trying to break into a space ATM, and she puts her focus on him, dodging asteroids and Zox's weapons, and putting her driving skills to the test against harrowing distractions!

removed.title: Up and Atom
removed.description: Wonder Woman and Batman are recruiting a reluctant Atom at his lab as a full time Justice Leaguer. "I make things little," he protests. "I'm not, like, a big fighty guy." The pitch is broken up by the explosive intrusion of Etrigan the Demon, who mops the floor with Wonder Woman and Batman when they try to send him back to the dark side. Does "little" guy Atom have enough fight in him? He'll find out once and for all if size matters!

removed.title: Something in the Hair
removed.description: Something's odd in the JL Watchtower, Batman has released Poison Ivy from lockup and is giving her a ride home! When Plastic Man protests, one fluff of Ivy's hair releases mind control spores, which he bats away. He follows her into the garage, where she and Batman, on the Batcycle, charge across a bridge of seaweed that Ivy has created toward Metropolis. Plastic Man gives chase, dodging the Batcycle's defensive gadgets. At the docks, there's one last chance for Plastic Man to keep himself alive and break the power of Ivy's spores.

removed.title: Toymano a Mano
removed.description: A hulking robot robs Gotham City National Bank, but it's Cyborg! Toyman has a remote to control his actions. Now Batman is pitted against his own friend, who whips the Batmobile behind him till Batman stops him with a tire "boot." In rocket shoes, Toyman propels himself to the harbor and onto a rubber ducky raft, actually a controlled Plastic Man, who Batman hooks before his ally becomes a reluctant escape airplane. Now Batman needs to call on all of his genius to save his friends.

removed.title: Beep Beep!
removed.description: Lobo has big plans to earn a $100 million bounty on The Flash and "retire on the beach." He uses a distress signal to lure Superman and the Flash to a desert planet (that looks a lot like the setting for Wile E. Coyote's attempts to catch Road Runner). He puts Superman out of commission with a Kryptonite ray gun and cage. Try as Lobo does to catch "the red speedster," the Flash gets around every one of his tricks in a funny salute to the Looney Tunes classics.

removed.title: Lasso of Lies
removed.description: Deadshot 's attempt to assassinate Wonder Woman leads her into a blind alley, where they punch it out as she demands to know who hired him. When she throws the Lasso of Truth around Deadshot, it turns into a limp, pink noodle with the voice of Plastic Man. Adding to the confusion, Booster Gold literally drops in holding the real lasso. An irritated Wonder Woman uses it to draw out some inconvenient truths from Booster Gold. But will she get the information she needs?

removed.title: True Colors
removed.description: Superman has Metallo subdued enough to take him back to prison, but when the arch-villain presses a button on his breastplate, it throws Superman in a Kryptonite spotlight, putting him on his knees. Firestorm tries to help, but keeps changing the harmful green Kryptonite into other colors, red, gold, pink and black. Chided by the professor, Firestorm tries hard to remember the formula to neutralize the deadly element.

removed.title: Quality Time
removed.description: Wonder Woman explains that "bonding is important" as they unite to fight fires, explosions, and tendrils of monstrous vines that choke off the city. It's all the work of Poison Ivy and her Ivy League. Her gigantic Venus Flytrap of a vine squeezes Batman, Star Sapphire bats away Superman's attempts to catch her, Cheetah puts the Flash out of commission, and Ember makes an explosive entrance to finish him off. Wonder Woman steps in to interrupt the mayhem so the boys can get back in the game. They're all for unity, except for the Dark Knight, but the game they end up with is hardly what anyone expected.

removed.title: Eezy Freezy
removed.description: Mr. Freeze has paralyzed Gotham City in ice and helps himself to a jewelry store's inventory. Batman catches him cold, but Mr. Freeze seems to be always two steps ahead of the hero. And Plastic Man's arrival certainly isn't going to help Batman catch Mr. Freeze, who's escaping on a motorcycle. Or will it?

removed.title: Chemistry
removed.description: HIVE has hit four major tech rooms, and Stargirl keeps an eye out to catch them in the act. But while she's waiting, flirty Firestorm would like nothing more than to impress her by shouting nerdy terms, coached by Prof. Martin Stein ("Keynesian economics, Hegelian dialecticism!") which makes her yawn. As she fends off HIVE's violent attack, Firestorm throws out theory after theory, but it's not helping much. Will he be able to use his own powers and dazzle her at the same time?

removed.title: Super Stakeout
removed.description: Green Arrow's stakeout of The Penguin's lair has come up with zero. As if that wasn't bad enough, Plastic Man arrives, in the form of a flying whoopee cushion, to help. Green Arrow gets rid of his loudmouth friend, who returns as a fire hydrant, a rat, and a cat to get closer to the Penguin's HQ. He finds the villain and his thugs, so he delivers himself to their door as a pizza. Inside, it's time to show what he can do against the Penguin and his minions. Now, where's Green Arrow?

removed.title: Mint Condition
removed.description: Cyborg has good news and bad. Good: he's added lots of new action figures to his collectible toys. Bad: Toyman has turned all the "Bot-Bots," which he's been collecting since childhood, into weapons. In the ensuing battle, a hysterical Cyborg needs to choose whether he's willing to destroy or damage his precious mint condition collectibles, or be a victim of their destruction. Will he stop the battle before they lose all their value, or will he allow Toyman, and his new toy army, to destroy Justice League's headquarters?

removed.title: Plastic Man of Steel
removed.description: Lois Lane believes that Clark Kent is Superman, so the Man of Steel enlists Plastic Man to put the doubt back by having him pose as Clark. Lois lures "Clark" to the Daily Planet rooftop and jumps to test him, but she's rescued by, Superman!  But he's hit with red Sun radiation beamed by an armored Lex Luthor, who wants a retraction of Lois's "lies" about him in the paper. The weakened Superman is no match for Luthor in (body armor), so Plastic Man has to stretch to the occasion.

removed.title: Clown Party
removed.description: The Joker and Batman duke it out on a Gotham City rooftop. In their between punch banter, Batman calls the Joker's jokes, "old, but never funny." The villain takes offense and drops a pair of gas bombs, then escapes the explosion with a jet pack, which gets taken down with a Batarang. He falls, spiraling right into a little kid's backyard birthday party. Now, the Joker gets to show off his comic timing with what he's always wanted, a captive audience!
